  footnotes: []
english:
  title: A Preface Sent with Monk Jigyeom to the Dharma Assembly at Gwangsu Temple in the Central Region
  author: Lim Chun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Someone once asked Lin Daeyeon, "Since you know Monk Jigyeom so well, tell me—what is the true nature of his way?"

    I replied: "My nature has always been drawn to the Buddhist path. For twenty years I searched for a true teacher and companion, never finding one—until now, through this monk, I have found what I sought.

    In this world, those who study Buddhism yet lack discipline and integrity inevitably resort to flowery writing as an excuse for their excess. Their work becomes bloated and hollow, stealing pretty phrases from the Confucian classics, stringing together ornate verses to dazzle the eyes and ears of the masses. They commit a great offense against Buddhism itself.

    But this monk stands apart. His spirit surpasses all others; his keen insight strikes like lightning. Wherever he goes among the assembly, even the most celebrated monks bow before him. He is truly a master of the dharma. Yet he is equally versed in the classical texts, learned and comprehensive in every way. His writing is vigorous and refined, far exceeding ordinary skill—and yet he hides it all, speaking as though he possessed no such gifts.

    Though I have walked with him for three years, he has never once mentioned these things. Puzzled, I finally asked him about it. Jigyeom smiled and said: 'I am devoted to dharma language, seeking the taste of sweet dew. How much more then should one who practices Zen avoid clinging to words as the first principle? How could I abandon careless speech and still contend with worldly scholars for fame?'

    Hearing these words, I revered him all the more.

    Now he departs, treading through emptiness toward the south to attend the great assembly at Gwangsu Temple. Long have I grieved at those who hide behind flowery words as a mask for their dissolution. So I write this to send with him.
  footnotes:
    - Lin Daeyeon (林大年) is likely a courtesy name or alternate designation for the author, Lim Chun.
    - The 'dharma assembly' (法會) refers to a Buddhist gathering for teaching and practice.
    - '''Dharma language'' (法語) in Zen Buddhism refers to direct pointing to truth beyond conceptual understanding.'
    - '''Sweet dew'' (甘露) is a classical metaphor for the nectar of Buddhist teachings, ultimate truth that sustains spiritual life.'
